That cleanly matches both the tech and the philosophy.

why it fits

The captain should be good at:
	•	goals
	•	priorities
	•	sequencing
	•	interpretation
	•	exceptions
	•	deciding when to continue, stop, or ask for help

The pilot should be good at:
	•	stabilization
	•	timing
	•	control loops
	•	sensor fusion
	•	low-latency correction
	•	not crashing

So:

captain = language, intent, strategy
pilot = control, balance, execution

That is much safer than asking the LLM to directly be the pilot.

beast stack

You could frame it like this:

user
→ beast llm captain
→ pilot/controller
→ actuators

sensors/vision
→ pilot/controller
→ beast llm captain (summaries, alerts, state)

So the pilot handles the fast loop.
The captain handles the slow loop.

example: model boat

User:

zora, attempt vectoring of model boat to center of lake

Captain decides:
	•	target = center
	•	mode = cautious
	•	strategy = move/observe/correct
	•	hand off to pilot

Pilot executes:
	•	thrust
	•	rudder correction
	•	stop timing
	•	heading stabilization

Captain monitors:
	•	are we making progress?
	•	are we drifting too much?
	•	do we need a new plan?
	•	do we abort?

best part

This lets Beast language stay useful without demanding impossible precision from the LLM.

The LLM can say:

fore
stop
left
hold
continue
abort

But the pilot interprets that into:
	•	motor values
	•	duration
	•	compensation
	•	smoothing

star trek framing

This is very bridge-crew.
	•	captain gives intent
	•	helm executes
	•	tactical advises
	•	sensors report
	•	captain updates plan

That feels much more Beast than "one giant model does everything."

